    "summary": "The Five Dynasties and Ten Kingdoms period (907–960 AD) was an era of political fragmentation following the collapse of the [[event:87|Tang Dynasty]] — a half-century during which northern China was ruled by five short-lived dynasties in rapid succession (Later Liang, Later Tang, Later Jin, Later Han, Later Zhou) while southern and peripheral China was divided among ten independent kingdoms. None of the northern dynasties lasted more than 16 years; emperors were made and unmade by military strongmen; and political instability was the defining characteristic of the era.\n\nDespite the political chaos, the Five Dynasties period was not culturally barren: the southern kingdoms (particularly the Southern Tang, Min, and Wu-Yue) were sophisticated states that patronized art, literature, and Buddhism. The era saw important technological developments — [[event:2158|woodblock printing]] expanded enormously, allowing the mass production of Buddhist texts and secular literature. The practical impossibility of governing China as multiple rival states — the inability to maintain the canal systems, tax collection, and military defense against northern nomads — created irresistible pressure for reunification, ultimately achieved when Zhao Kuangyin founded the [[event:2156|Song Dynasty]] in 960 AD. The instability of this period reinforced the Song dynasty's decision to strengthen civilian control over the military, contributing to the Song's later military weakness but cultural sophistication.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Five_Dynasties_and_Ten_Kingdoms_period",
